[1] Lethal yellowing, coconut palm - Jamaica: update
Date: 23 Mar 2008
Source: The Jamaica Observer [edited]
<http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/news/html/20080322T200000-0500_133771_OBS_COCONUT_KILLER_.asp>


An outbreak of the devastating lethal yellowing disease is
threatening coconut palms across the island, spurring the Coconut
Industry Board (CIB) to recommend that all infected plants be
immediately cut down and burned. "We have seen hot spots all over the
island, but it is now showing up highly concentrated in the eastern
parishes," said Edgar Watson, general manager of the Coconut Industry
Board (CIB).

A resurgence of lethal yellowing could wipe out the island's coconut
palm population, killing an industry already under pressure from
substitute oils and synthetic products. Dr Wayne Myrie, plant
pathologist at the Board, suggested that the plant should ideally be
cut down at the 1st stage. "It is a culling procedure that is used
with many other commodities," Watson said. The CIB is also advocating
the use of legumes as cover crop, and special attention given to soil
fertility.

Problems with lethal yellowing go back more than 100 years in the
Caribbean. It was discovered in Cayman Islands in 1834 and 50 years
later showed up in the western end of Jamaica. The 1st major outbreak
occurred in 1961; the 1st case being in Buff Bay before afflicting
the major coconut growing parishes in the eastern end of the island.
More than 8 million palms were destroyed during that outbreak. Then
in the 1970s, research led to the introduction of the Malayan Dwarf
and later a local hybrid named Maypan, both of which were believed to
be resistant to the disease. However in 1988, palms including the
Malayan dwarf again displayed symptoms of the disease.

[Byline: by Patrick Foster]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

