[4] Kerala wilt, coconut palm - India: phytoplasma characterisation and vectors
Date: September 2007
Source: Physiological and Molecular Plant Pathology 71, 41-47 [edited]
<http://www.sciencedirect.com/science?_ob=ArticleURL&_udi=B6WPC-4PYYTRT-1&_user=162644&_rdoc=1&_fmt=&_orig=search&_sort=d&view=c&_acct=C000013138&_version=1&_urlVersion=0&_userid=162644&md5=54f1bd59fc51bc0c5c6bd2d652dbc031>
(subscription only)


Kerala wilt disease of coconut palm is a major threat of coconut
production in Kerala caused by phytoplasma. The genomic DNA purified
from the insect tissues of _Proutista moesta_ (PM) and _Stephanitis
typica_ (ST) was subjected to PCR [Polymerase Chain Reaction] assay.
The presence of a 650 basepair product from _P. moesta_ indicates the
vectoral ability of the insect. No sign of amplification was noticed
in the case of ST, suggesting the inability of this insect as vector.
The sequential similarity of the 650 bp of both KWD phytoplasma and
the insect phytoplasma supports the transmission of phytoplasma
through the vector PM.

Moreover, the sequence of 650 bp was compared with other sequences of
26 coconut phytoplasmas so far reported internationally, and a
cladogram was prepared for determining the phylogenetic status. It is
obvious from the cladogram that the KWD disease phytoplasma is
evolutionarily closest to the phytoplasma of coconut lethal yellowing
of Mexican palms within the group 16SrIV. Phylogenetically, KWD
phytoplasma is grouped in the new subgroup 16SrIV-C subsequent to the
groups 16SrIV-A and 16SrIV-B for Mexican coconut lethal yellowing and
Tanzanian coconut lethal decline, respectively.

This records the 1st finding of the vector of Kerala wilt disease by
detecting KWD phytoplasma in insect tissue of PM by PCR-based
methods. Moreover, the study reveals the phylogenetic status of KWD
phytoplasma compared to other coconut phytoplasmas internationally.

[Byline: B. Edwin and C. Mohankumar]

--
Communicated by:
Hugh Harries
Editor, Google Coconut Group
<http://groups.google.com/group/coconut?hl=en>


[Coconut palm is a vitally important subsistence and cash crop in
many poor regions, so much so that it is often called the "Tree of
Life". A number of phytoplasma diseases are known to affect this crop.

1. Lethal yellowing (LY) is caused by _Candidatus_ Phytoplasma palmae
and is spreading in the Americas and parts of Africa. It has
seriously jeopardised coconut industries in affected areas and can
infect a large number of palm species, killing trees usually within 4
to 6 months. Planthopper vectors, possible seed transmission, and
weed reservoirs are thought to be involved in LY epidemiology. For
more information on LY, see previous ProMED-mail post no. 20080125.0313.

2. Cape St Paul wilt (CSPW) disease in Ghana is caused by a related
phytoplasma of the palm lethal yellowing (16SrIV) taxonomic group. A
number of other LY group strains have been described from different
regions. The vectors for CSPW and some of the other LY phytoplasmas
are not known yet, but seed-transmission has been reported. For more
information on CSPW, see previous ProMED-mail post no. 20071224.4129.

3. In Asia, a number of coconut diseases caused by phytoplasmas are
known, for example Natuna and Kalimantan wilts in Indonesia, and
Kerala wilt (KW) in India. The KW phytoplasma was thought to belong
to a separate taxonomic group, but the above report [4] has now
placed it as a species within the lethal yellowing group. It is
spread by insect vectors, but there is no evidence of seed
transmission. The disease is not lethal, but significantly reduces
production. For more information on KW, see previous ProMED-mail post
no. 20080105.0063.

Symptoms of these phytoplasmas may be suppressed by regular
tetracycline applications, but commercial control is primarily being
achieved by replanting with resistant varieties. Recent observations
of breakdown of resistance to the LY phytoplasma of some widely used
hybrids are causing great concern for coconut replanting programmes
worldwide. Reasons for the breakdown are still uncertain and may
include genetic variation of either the host, the pathogen, or the vector.

The report [2] above seems to exclude genetic contamination of
Malayan Dwarf varieties as a sole source of resistance breakdown.
Similar work has been carried out by the same researchers to check
the genetic background of Panama Tall in Jamaica. Malayan Dwarf and
Panama Tall are the parents of the widely used "resistant" MAYPAN
hybrid. While some contamination primarily from the highly
susceptible Jamaican Tall was detected, this seemed insufficient to
be the only cause of the latest outbreak of the disease. Neither the
MAYPAN nor its parents can be considered resistant in the present
context of Jamaica (M. Dollet, personal communication).

